05569nam a22006615i 9780773557918DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735579187 a10.1515/97807735579182doi  a(DE-B1597)656152  a(OCoLC)1085895940  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aHIS0150002bisacsh04a791.0942qOCoLC223/eng/2023112000aEarly Modern Spectatorship :bInterpreting English Culture, 1500-1780 /ced. by David McNeil, Ronald Huebert. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b44 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tBibliographical Note -- tPreface -- tEarly Modern Spectatorship: An Overview -- tMaking Spectacles: Spectatorship and Authority on the Early Modern Stage -- t“Shame's pure blush”: Shakespeare and the Ethics of Spectatorship -- tSpectatorship and Repression in Shakespeare's Twelfth Night -- t“Most grateful deceptions of the sight”: Optical Technologies in Restoration England -- tDying in Earnest: Public Executions and Their Audiences -- tLooking at John Donne Looking at God -- tSidney Visualized: Thomas Lant's Sequitur celebritas (1588) and the Funeral Construction of an English National Hero -- t“Watching the Watchers”: The Spectatorship Game in Ned Ward's The London Spy -- tProspect Views: Landscapes, Knowledge, and Political Spectatorship in the Eighteenth Century -- tA Case Study on Spectatorship and the Visual Arts: Democritus and Heraclitus -- tSpectacle and the Chronotope of Progress in William Hogarth's London -- tMural Painting and Spectatorship in Early Eighteenth-Century Britain -- tIllustrations -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat did it mean to be a spectator during the lifetime of Shakespeare or of Aphra Behn? In Early Modern Spectatorship contributors use the idea of spectatorship to reinterpret canonical early modern texts and bring visibility to relatively unknown works. While many early modern spectacles were designed to influence those who watched, the very presence of spectators and their behaviour could alter the conduct and the meaning of the event itself. In the case of public executions, for example, audiences could both observe and be observed by the executioner and the condemned. Drawing on work in the digital humanities and theories of cultural spectacle, these essays discuss subjects as various as the death of Desdemona in Othello, John Donne's religious orientation, Ned Ward's descriptions of London, and Louis Laguerre's murals painted for the residences of English aristocrats. A lucid exploration of subtle questions, Early Modern Spectatorship identifies, imagines, and describes the spectator's experience in early modern culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArts audienceszEnglandxHistory. 0aPerforming artsxAudienceszEnglandxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh1 aBowers, Rick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruyn, Fans de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamlett, Lydia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuebert, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuebert, Ronald, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLepage, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcAdam, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcNeil, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcNeil, David, eeditor.4edt